#compdef ffizer
# =============================================================================
# ffizer — David Bernard's "files and folders initializer / generator"
#          — a Rust CLI scaffolding tool for creating projects from
#          Git/local templates with variable substitution, conditional
#          file inclusion, and reapply-after-template-update support.
#          Distinguishing from cookiecutter (Python), copier (Python),
#          yeoman (Node), kickstart (Rust, R-prev), and casey/cargo-
#          generate (Rust) by:
#            - REAPPLY MODE — `ffizer reapply` re-runs a previously-
#              applied template against an existing project to pick
#              up template updates; tracks applied templates via
#              .ffizer/journal.yml
#            - JSON SCHEMA SHIPPED — `ffizer show-json-schema` emits
#              the JSON Schema for .ffizer.yaml files; editor LSPs +
#              CI validation can use this directly
#            - SAMPLE TESTING — `ffizer test-samples` runs a
#              template against bundled sample inputs + checks
#              expected outputs (regression testing for templates)
#            - 3 UPDATE MODES via --update-mode (Ask/Override/Keep/
#              UpdateAsTemplated/CurrentAsTemplated/Merge) for
#              handling existing files when reapplying
#            - 3 CONFIRMATION MODES via --confirm (Always/Never/
#              Auto) — Auto detects TTY + adjusts behavior
#            - OFFLINE MODE via --offline — uses only cached
#              templates from .ffizer/cache/; useful in air-gapped
#              environments
#            - PER-VARIABLE OVERRIDES via -v key=value (repeatable)
#              — pass template variables via CLI without prompts
#            - GIT TEMPLATE SOURCE — templates can be local paths
#              OR Git URLs (full URL or short owner/repo) with
#              optional --rev / --subfolder
#            - --no-interaction (-y) — skip all prompts (CI-friendly)
#            - VERBOSE MODE via -v / -vv / -vvv (counted) — info /
#              debug / trace levels routed to stderr
#            - walkdir DIRECTORY TRAVERSAL — every template file
#              walking + path matching uses BurntSushi's walkdir
#              for fast cross-platform directory traversal
#          Used by: project scaffolding workflows, polyglot
#          monorepo template management, language-agnostic
#          generator pipelines (any language template), and as
#          a reference implementation of walkdir + clap-derive
#          + git2-rs Rust CLI design.
